Nothing very impressive, compared to global exchanges in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) has been interested in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "in competition with the dollar or the euro" and "like conventional currencies".
Bitcoin is distinguished from other types of virtual currency such as "credits", used to advance in a video game that you win by playing or you can buy (and sometimes exchange in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed this type of system.
But, every time, a central authority controls and handles exchanges.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are both accounts book depositors, checkers, currency emitters, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two email addresses in the way of an email.
Unless a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring the anonymity.
