Just before the war, all projects for use of the fuse technique were conducted by the provisional scientific advisory committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other work dedicated to the airline were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish astronaut company (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, it is about a company in the November 1954 issue magazine, in which four more detailed articles about aviation.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronomy.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had the future.
In the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronaut Society (PTA) made efforts to enter the International Astronaut Federation (created in 1951) and in the autumn, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Vice-President of the International Astronaut Federation.
He maintained his office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has contributed significantly to the successful development of the RM Meteorologiczna (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which has become the first Polish missile to conduct scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This 1800-metre missile was 80 cm long and weighed slightly less than 5 kg.
An improved version was later built, RM-1A, and during the summer of 1959 two-storey RM-2 missile flight tests were launched in the Bledov desert.
This missile was 1.4 meters long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The following prototype should have been able to perform concrete scientific works - the RM-34 missile should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development works were stopped.
The Meteor-1 missile developed during the period 1962 - 1965, followed by the first RM-type missiles.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (so-called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A missile had a space offering a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B the volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C was 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of engines was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 missiles were deployed at the Aeronautical Institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 missile had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful load of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were later built.
It is also worth mentioning the entry of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a COSPAR National Committee two years later.
Under the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in the space exploration of artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of the program.
