In November 1979, a crowd of protesters composed of Islamic students attacked the U.S. Embassy of Tehran and detained 52 diplomats.
They had to be released in exchange for Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, who supported his regime for decades.
The situation would not offer positive consequences to the U.S. administration, it could not, in fact, abandon the Shah, because it would severely break down the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the liberation of captives.
It was a hard hit for the US prestige, a hit further aggravated by the fiasco attempt to release the captives by force.
The seized diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following the Algerian government's negotiations.
Their fate triggers a wave of solidarity and an anti-Iran feeling in the United States.
The Iranian debtor contributed strongly to Jimmy Carter’s defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo, the actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story offering a small victory to America.
Just before she was occupied, six employees escaped the embassy.
After complicated incidents, they found themselves in the residence of the Ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran through a rock cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a tournament team coming to make surveys for filming a large-scale science fiction film.
Combination of genres
Tony Mendez’s exfiltration expert’s plan requires Hollywood’s collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized stores stated this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, and the film was based on Tony Mendez’s memories.
The Affleck film is an unusual combination of several genres.
It is a part of a political thriller designed realistically but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful hit, a traitor - such as, for example, in the Ocean's eleven trilogy, twelve and thirteen.
The environment follows: The Tehran sequences of documentary style (in the subtitles are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and how, thanks to these photos, the same situations have been retranslated in the film, there are no major differences),
lighter passages from Hollywood, treated with irony and a bit of excess,
and then scenes of the CIA headquarters and other institutions with costume men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the hallways and on the phone.
Ben Affleck managed to restart his career remarkably.
As a ridiculous actor, he became a respected scener and his game as an actor ceased to excite ironic observations.
Argo is his third long film after the dark policeman "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It is also the first film that does not take place in his original city, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above the Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of the atmosphere in Argo where Tehran’s role is “managed” by Canada.
