Szabo: "The Germans must play a bigger role."
Germany chose the abstention during the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the United States and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the request of Palestinians to obtain observer status from the United Nations.
But she then chose the abstention.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not agree with what Israel did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious because it maintains special relations with Israel.
But I also think it does not support the American position.
Germany wanted to affirm its independence, however, without being too critical to Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany had also chosen the abstention during the vote on the establishment of an air-exclusion zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany have difficulty adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to get away from a policy defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
In addition, the lack of coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans are struggling on several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're still trying to find this role, but they're on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, such as France or Britain
What does the term "normal" foreign policy then mean for the Germans?
It demonstrates its willingness to adopt independent positions from the United States and European partners, including in national cases.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, so by exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to some extent, different from those of the other great powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position towards the Middle East conflict and the abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany first has significant markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
Therefore, Berlin must be careful not to strike the public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is certainly a decisive element.
However, I would not give it too much importance, because it is not a single-sided relationship.
But this is, in any case, a decisive element in German strategic thoughts.
Does Germany harm its relations with the United States by choosing the abstention during important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That's why I think the fracture is not so serious that it was in the case of the Libyan issue.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, the opinions on the Palestinian initiative are different.
On the other hand, the United States announced its veto with a clear voice.
Are opinions different between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences due to the U.S. internal political scene.
I believe that the Obama administration secretly demonstrates a great understanding of the European position.
But because of the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I think the real differences in opinions are not so big that they always look like it.
If you observe the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far beyond enthusiasm for Netanyahu’s policy.
Does Germany have difficulty reconciliating its close relationships with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I don't think it makes things easier for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not the case.
They cannot, therefore, register within a broader political line and must affirm their single position.
That is what they are currently doing in the euro issue.
In my opinion, Germany will take a role as a locomotive in the future and will force Europe to adopt a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This question has always been delicate.
But in my opinion, the Germans are well aware of the fact that they have to play a role that marks their independence more.
Does Germany play a role as a weight actor on the international stage, is Germany just wanting to take a key role?
Or does it still have difficulties to take top roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable for him and, for obvious reasons, the country is still experiencing difficulties to play a more important role.
For example, if we look at the euro crisis, we notice that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make things easier for the Germans.
In fact, this is still the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It must be composed with very diverse neighbors and opinions, and it is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy only reduces, but at the moment the EU does not fill this vacuum, so what remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and if they're just less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, a institute in which universities and policy experts in Europe and North America together analyze the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German policy, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
