Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth (Texas), became globally known for the main role of John Ross Ewing, more known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he incarnated a scrupulous, scary and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as scrupulous J.R. Ewing's oil magnate in the Dallas TV series has become a symbol of avarice in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who had returned this year to the role of J.R in a new Dallas season, died Friday evening of cancer complications, according to a family statement sent to The Associad Press for Warner Bros., Dallas production house.
“Larry was back to his dear native town in Dallas, playing again the ironic role he loved most,” the family said.
Larry's family and his close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played the role of her wife in the original series and later, was with Hagman when he died in a hospital in Dallas, said her press attachment, Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to all those who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, enthusiastic and talented, and I will miss him a lot.
"He was an exceptional person and he was living life deeply," Gray said in a statement.
Doctors had diagnosed a liver cirrhosis at Larry Hagman in 1992 and had admitted that he had been drinking a lot for many years.
In 1995, a liver malignancy was detected and he had a stroke.
