A course about "The End of the World" has just begun
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to give a course at the end of the world, he knew that he was launching an irresistible chastisement: the end of the "big count" of the Maya calendar, on December 21, to which many people refer as the proof of the end of the imminent world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what was expecting him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a tax burden that some have called the "Armageddon of Debt" and a growing conflict that involves Israel, the place where Christian theories of the end of time thought it would trigger the apocalypse.
“I didn’t realize that this would be the most apocalyptic semester I’ve ever known,” Professor Charmé told his students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If we analyze what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we told it, it was a very good time.
And it must be remembered that what is bad is good for those who believe in apocalypse.
And he is not the only teacher to give lessons on the "final of the world" this semester, which, in theory, will be the last of history.
At Temple, Deputy Professor Barry Vacker dispenses the "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
"We analyze this because these ideas spread over time," he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios leads a certain human behavior.
If the nuclear weapon fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could collapse.
This month, students will analyze movies with apocalyptic themes and learn how they can be compared to real life examples.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible and impossible," Vacker said.
On the main campus of the State University of Pennsylvania, professor Matthew Restall of Latin America’s History and his colleague Amara Solari, a deputy professor of History of Art and Anthropology, made a team to give a course, simply titled "The End of the World".
"We add "2012" to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world would not disappear," Professor Restall said.
Despite the “imminent disaster,” students need to study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final examination will be held in the evening of the Apocalypse, which leaves students no choice but to work "until the night of the presumed end of the world," Restall said.
The courses have proved quite popular.
"It was complete in two hours," Restall said about his course for high-level students, consisting of 35 students.
We received email messages several weeks before the beginning of the semester, from people who asked if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves,” says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in religion and sociology, originating from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers-Camden University.
Because fear of Apocalypse, whether it is century or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or absence of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student in Psychology and Nursing, says he has seen all the apocalyptic films.
“I’ve never heard of a course that taught this matter,” he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students questioned, and even less a teacher, told us to believe in the end date of the world of December 21.
"Our first project was about the Maya prophecy, and in some way we discredited it," said Julie Zegle, a last year student at Temple, 21 years old, originating from West Chester.
The Mayas have never predicted the end of the world, it’s just a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I confess that there is an anxiety related to apocalypse in Western culture, back to several centuries, which makes people react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a rise of these speculations.
“In other places around the globe, people don’t think about it,” he says.
This is mostly the English-speaking world.
